    thinking: "**Listing Available Models**\n\nI\'ve been looking at available models within the `gemini-api` skill. Currently, I\'ve identified `gemini-3.5-flash`, which is suited for text tasks like summarization, proofreading, and simple Q&A. It appears to be a very fast, standard option. Also, `gemini-1.5-pro` is a more advanced option.\n\n\n**Refining Model Selection**\n\nI\'m now focusing on model selection, particularly for Q&A and training plan generation. Considering the available API keys, I propose using `gemini-3.5-flash` for the Q&A chats, which is fast and efficient. For training plans, I\'m leaning toward the same or a more detailed prompt structure. The UI will offer users \"Groq (Llama 3 - Veloce)\" and \"Premium Model\" options, but the backend will default to a Gemini client using `gemini-3.5-flash` if API keys aren\'t provided. I\'ll check for any necessary package installations next.\n\n\n**Designing TCX Parser**\n\nI\'ve decided to create a dedicated file, `server/tcxParser.ts`, to house the TCX parser for cleaner code. Initially, I thought RegExp, but I\'ll write a robust parser since TCX is XML. I\'ve started examining the file structure, specifically looking at `<Activity>`, `<Id>`, and `<Creator>` tags. Also, I\'m noting specific lap details like `<DistanceMeters>`, `<TotalTimeSeconds>`, and heart rate data within the file.\n\n\n**Developing Robust TCX Parsing**\n\nI\'m now focusing on a more sophisticated TCX parsing function. It must handle nested tags accurately, so I\'m updating the parsing function to find and extract the lap data, including distance, duration, heart rate, calories, and cadence. I am aiming to aggregate the results. I will also develop an extremely robust parsing function. It\'s time to build the folder structure for the project.\n\n\n**Defining Project Structure**\n\nI am now structuring the project. I\'m focusing on defining core components: `/src/components/Chat.tsx` for the AI coach chat with Fast/Premium toggle, auto-trigger, and Markdown rendering, along with `/src/components/History.tsx`, which will list runs with detailed lap data and host the TCX upload zone. I\'m also creating `/src/types.ts` to define interfaces for Activity, Lap, ChatMessage, and Stats. The existing `.env.example` file is already in the project! I\'ll investigate its contents to understand the environment variables.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will create `/src/types.ts` to define the shared TypeScript types for Activities, Laps, Chat Messages, and Running Stats, ensuring complete type safety across both frontend and backend."
