  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Constructing the Server**\n\nOkay, the TCX parser is complete, featuring helpful utilities and accurate file parsing. Now, I\'m shifting focus to creating the Express server at `/server.ts`. I need to ensure that it aligns with the \"Full-Stack Applications (Express + Vite)\" instructions, and meets the requirements as detailed in the prompt.\n\n\n**Implementing the API Endpoints**\n\nNow, I\'m focusing on implementing the API endpoints following the `gemini-api` guidelines. I\'ve got the standard initialization of the GoogleGenAI client set up, complete with telemetry headers. The plan is to handle the `/api/stats`, `/api/activities`, and `/api/upload-tcx` endpoints. I\'m especially eager to get the `POST /api/chat` logic working, particularly the training plan detection and integration of `ai.models.generateContent` with the GoogleGenAI client.\n\n\n**Adapting the API Client**\n\nI\'m making a key adjustment to the API client initialization. My thought is to prioritize Groq and OpenAI API keys if they\'re provided in `process.env`. If `GROQ_API_KEY` or `PREMIUM_API_KEY` are set, I\'ll leverage their respective APIs, falling back to Google\'s Gemini API if not. This offers users a choice of LLMs. I\'m excited about this flexibility, and I\'m adding the logic for the Groq API call, which I can call through a simple fetch request!\n\n\n**Expanding API Endpoint Choices**\n\nI\'m now focusing on expanding the LLM options for the API. I\'ve been reflecting on how to ensure flexibility for the user in choosing their preferred API. I will use standard fetch calls to Groq, OpenAI, and Anthropic\'s endpoints, without requiring any third-party SDK dependencies. Groq will use the `llama-3.3-70b-versatile` model. For the premium API, I\'ll allow users to specify a base URL and model via environment variables; and I will fall back to Gemini\'s models if necessary.\n\n\n**Refining Model Selection**\n\nI\'m now refining the model selection within the Gemini API framework. My thinking is to offer seamless options: \"Fast\" can leverage `gemini-3.5-flash` with a low temperature, and \"Premium\" can use the same model but with an extensive coach system prompt to generate detailed plans, potentially using tables or bullet points. If a user provides a paid key, I\'ll allow `gemini-3.1-pro-preview`. I\'m also planning to implement `GET /api/chat-history` to read messages, and `POST /api/chat-clear` to clear and reset the history. I will double-check that the Vite Middleware is configured according to guidelines.\n\n\n**Finalizing Server Implementation**\n\nNow I\'m focusing on the server\'s implementation, making sure the API routes are initialized first. I\'ve also incorporated Vite middleware for development as the prompt requires. The production build uses the dist folder for static assets. I\'m especially focused on implementing the system prompt for the coach. I have to design a motivating and technically accurate running coach system prompt in Italian.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will create the `/server.ts` full-stack entry point. It configures Express, uses `multer` for memory-based TCX file uploads, sets up the shared `@google/genai` SDK client, integrates Groq and Premium proxy models (as requested, with fallback to the local Gemini client), defines the Italian coaching system prompt, and hosts the static/Vite middleware correctly."
    thinking_duration {
